ifferences in early language environments shape children's language development / rWeisleder, Adriana / Marchman, Virginia A. -- t27. Cognition and language in different socioeconomic and environmental settings / rSchibli, Kylie / Hedayati, Nina / Hobbs, Hannah / Sheik-Ahmed, Amina / D'Angiulli, Amedeo -- t28. Language disorder versus language difference: The impact of socio-economic status / rLetts, Carolyn -- tIII Environmental effects Section 7: Multilingualism -- t29. Input, context and early child bilingualism: Implications for clinical practice / rHouwer, Annick De -- t30. SLI in bilingual development: How do we approach assessment? / rArmon-Lotem, Sharon -- t31. Development of vocabulary knowledge and its relationship with reading comprehension among emergent bilingual children: An overview / rProctor, C. Patrick / Louick, Rebecca -- t32. Factors affecting second language acquisition: Successes and nonsuccesses / rGass, Susan -- tIV. Language and communication disorders Section 8: Developmental and neurological disorders -- t33 .The changing profile of Specific Language Impairment / rJong, Jan de -- t34. Neuroplasticity and development: Discourse in children with perinatal stroke and children with language impairment / rPolse, Lara R. / Engel, Samantha M. / Reilly, Judy S. -- t35 .Types of developmental dyslexia / rFriedmann, Naama / Coltheart, Max -- t36. Implicit learning in developmental dyslexia as demonstrated by the Serial Reaction Time (SRT) and the Artificial Grammar Learning (AGL) tasks / rSchiff, Rachel / Vakil, Eli / Gabay, Yafit / Kahta, Shani -- t37. Speech and language in congenitally deaf children with a cochlear implant / rGillis, Steven -- t38. Parental involvement in early intervention for children with hearing loss / rIngber, Sara / Most, Tova -- t39. Communication, language, and speech in young children with autism spectrum disorder (ASD) / rDromi, Esther / Rum, Yonat / Florian, Jessica Goldberg -- t40. Language in people with Williams syndrome / rLevy, Yonata -- t41. Making language accessible for people with cognitive disabilities: Intellectual disability as a test case / rUziel-Karl, Sigal / Tenne-Rinde, Michal -- tIV Language and communication disorders Section 9: Disorders in aging -- t42. Brain and language in healthy aging / rHigby, Eve / Cahana-Amitay, Dalia / Obler, Loraine K. -- t43. Language impairments in acquired aphasia: Features and frameworks / rVarley, Rosemary / Zimmerer, Vitor -- t44 .Language in neurodegenerative diseases / rAssal, Frédéric / Laurent, Ariane -- tIndex  aThe domain of Communication Disorders has grown exponentially in the last two decades and has come to encompass much more than audiology, speech impediments and early language impairment. The realization that most developmental and learning disorders are language-based or language-related has brought insights from theoretical and empirical linguistics and its clinical applications to the forefront of Communication Disorders science. The current handbook takes an integrated psycholinguistic, neurolinguistic, and sociolinguistic perspective on Communication Disorders by targeting the interface between language and cognition as the context for understanding disrupted abilities and behaviors and providing solutions for treatment and therapy. Researchers and practitioners will be able to find in this handbook state-of-the-art information on typical and atypical development of language and communication (dis)abilities across the human lifespan from infancy to the aging brain, covering all major clinical disorders and conditions in various social and communicative contexts, such as spoken and written language and discourse, literacy issues, bilingualism, and socio-economic status.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Mai 2018) 4aAngewandte Linguistik